Created in 1981 9.0 by the U.S. greeting card company [[American Greetings]],<ref>{{cite book| last = Mansour| first = David| title = From ABBA to Zoom A Pop Culture Encyclopedia of the Late 20th Century| url = https://books.google.com/?id=hK0rPUF85loC&pg=PA70| accessdate = 2010-08-10| year = 2005| publisher = [[Andrews McMeel Publishing]]| isbn = 0-7407-5118-2| page = 70 }}</ref> the [[Care Bears]] are a group of characters that have appeared in various media.  Since early 1983, various companies in the Americas, Europe and Israel have published books based on the franchise.  In the United States, the Care Bears' books have been available through [[Random House]], [[Parker Brothers]] and [[Scholastic Books]].

==English-language books==

===Parker Brothers===
[[Parker Brothers]], a board game company then owned by [[General Mills]], launched its book publishing division in February 1983;<ref name=miami>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=KLslAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EfMFAAAAIBAJ&pg=6961,2049534&dq=care-bears&hl=en|last=Dougherty|first=Philip H.|agency=[[The New York Times Company|New York Times News Service]]|title=Parker Bros. adding book publishing line|date=February 8, 1983|accessdate=August 9, 2010|work=[[The Miami News]]|page=8A}}</ref> its first series consisted of six books featuring the Care Bears.<ref name=miami/><ref name=rules>{{cite book| last = Wojahn| first = Ellen| title = Playing by Different Rules| year = 1988| publisher = American Management Association (amacom)| isbn = 0-8144-5861-0 }}</ref>{{rp|155–156}}  Various authors contributed to the resulting series, ''Tales from the Care Bears''; Tom Cooke illustrated most of the stories.  At the time of publication, various trade publications took note of Parker Brothers' unique marketing strategy for the books.<ref name=rules/>{{rp|156}}  On October 30, 1987,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/0706430530/|title=Product information for ''Tales from the Care Bears''|accessdate=August 13, 2010|publisher=Amazon.com Inc}}</ref> Great Britain's [[Hamlyn (publishers)|Octopus Books]] released a book under this title ({{ISBN|0-7064-3053-0}}),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/tales-from-the-care-bears/oclc/18325762|title=Catalog information for ''Tales from the Care Bears''|accessdate=August 13, 2010|work=WorldCat|publisher=Online Computer Library Center (OCLC)}}</ref> containing Amelia Hubert's ''Sweet Dreams for Sally'' and Evelyn Mason's ''A Sister for Sam''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://copac.ac.uk/search?rn=1&isn=0706430530|title=Catalog record for ''Tales from the Care Bears''|accessdate=August 13, 2010|location=[[University of Manchester]]|publisher=[[Copac]]}}</ref>

Parker Brothers spent US$1 million in advertising on the original six-book series, which was made to promote the Care Bears characters.  According to a company spokesperson, the stories would demonstrate "love, caring, dreams, happiness, friendship, wishes, and feelings".  The series made its debut at the 1983 [[American International Toy Fair]], along with other Care Bears products.<ref name=rules/>{{rp|155}}  John Keller, editorial director for the books, commented on their creation:

{{quote|The old way was to give authors their head. We, on the other hand, make up a list of, say, thirty interesting plot ideas, and then we do consumer testing ... Once I have the rankings, I call up my pool of authors and give them a plot to work with, and a style sheet explaining the characters. And then I say, "Please write 2,500 words filled with verve and excitement."<ref name=rules/>{{rp|155–156}}}}

