{{refimprove|date=March 2013}} {{Infobox settlement | name = Sanganakallu | native_name = ಸಂಗನಕಲ್ಲು | native_name_lang = kn | other_name = Sanganakal | nickname = | settlement_type = Village | image_skyline = | image_alt = | image_caption = | pushpin_map = India Karnataka | pushpin_label_position = right | pushpin_map_alt = | coordinates = {{coord|15|11|5|N|76|58|13|E|display=inline,title}} | subdivision_type = Country | subdivision_name = {{flag|India}} | subdivision_type1 = [[States and territories of India|State]] | subdivision_name1 = [[Karnataka]] | subdivision_type2 = [[List of districts of India|District]] | subdivision_name2 = [[Bellary district]] | subdivision_type3 = [[Taluks of Karnataka|Taluk]] | subdivision_name3 = [[Bellary]] | subdivision_type4 = [[List of Constituencies of the Lok Sabha|Lok Sabha Constituency]] | subdivision_name4 = | established_title = <!-- Established --> | established_date = | founder = | named_for = | government_type = | governing_body = | unit_pref = Metric | area_footnotes = | area_rank = | area_total_km2 = | elevation_footnotes = | elevation_m = | population_total = | population_as_of = 2001 | population_rank = | population_density_km2 = | population_demonym = | population_footnotes = | demographics_type1 = Languages | demographics1_title1 = Official | demographics1_info1 = [[Kannada]] | timezone1 = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]] | utc_offset1 = +5:30 | postal_code_type = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]] | postal_code = | area_code_type = Telephone code | area_code = | registration_plate = KA 34 | website = | footnotes = }}
'''Sanganakallu''' ({{Lang-kn | ಸಂಗನಕಲ್ಲು }}) is an ancient archaeological site from the Neolithic period (circa 3000 BC). It is approximately 8&nbsp;km from [[Bellary]] in [[Karnataka]].<ref name=":0" /> It is a group of hills south of a horseshoe shaped valley, with Kupgal to the north.<ref name=":12">{{Cite book|title=Stone Age Cultures of Bellary|last=Subbarao|first=Bendapudi|publisher=Dr. S. M. Katre|year=1948|isbn=|location=Deccan College Postgraduate and Research Institute|pages=}}</ref> It is one of the earliest settlements in [[South India]], spread over 1,000 acres.<ref name=":0">{{cite web |url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/28818/early-village-unearthed.html |title=Early village unearthed |publisher= |accessdate=2012-09-25 }}</ref> There is a layer of red-brown [[Fossil|fossilized]] soil spread over Sanganakallu and Kupgal that can be dated back to 9000 BC.<ref name=":33">{{Cite book|title=The Prehistory and Protohistory of India and Pakistan|last=Sankalia|first=H. D.|publisher=|year=1974|isbn=|location=Deccan College Postgraduate and Research Institute, Poona|pages=}}</ref> The site is considered to be a [[neolithic]] factory site due to the surface excavation revealing large numbers of pottery, stone axes, and other [[Stone tool|stone tools]].<ref name=":12" /> The site was first majorly excavated in 1946, by Bendapudi Subbarao, on Sannarasamma hill.<ref name=":12" /> Subbarao divided their culture into 3 phases:<ref name=":12" /> * Pre-[[Mesolithic]], the phase when Sanganakallu was first settled, had little pottery, and the people made crude [[Microlith|microliths]]. * [[Mesolithic]], the phase when pottery was handmade and stone axes were mass produced. * [[Neolithic]], the phase when pottery and tools became more sophisticated.<ref name=":12" /> Sanganakallu was excavated again in 1964.<ref name=":22">{{Cite book|title=Excavation at Sangankallu, 1964-65|last=Ansari|first=Zainuddin|last2=Rao|first2=M. S.|publisher=|year=1969|isbn=|location=Poona|pages=}}</ref>
== Tools == The earliest tools excavated were hundreds of [[patinated]] [[Lithic flake|flakes]] made of [[basalt]], and [[quartz]] [[Lithic flake|flakes]].<ref name=":33" /> In the later Mesolithic phase is when tool making became more abundant.<ref name=":12" /> Stone axes, [[Hammerstone|hammer stones]], [[Chisel|chisels]], picks, slick-stones, and [[Sling (weapon)|sling stones]] were excavated.<ref name=":12" /> The axes were found in many different shapes. There were oval shaped, triangular shaped, or rectangular shaped axes and some were axes were rounded and some were thin.<ref name=":12" /> The sheer number of [[Microlith|microliths]] is the reason Sanganakallu is considered a factory site.<ref name=":12" />
== Pottery == The first pottery started showing up in Mesolithic phase. The pottery was usually dull brown or black, and hand-made out of course clay.<ref name=":12" /> Pale-gray pots made of fine clay mixed with [[Lime (material)|lime]] and [[mica]] were also excavated.<ref name=":12" /> The pottery from the later [[Megalith|Neolithic]] period were more fine, thin, and polished.<ref name=":12" /> They were all burnt and wheel turned.<ref name=":12" /> The ornamental pottery was decorated in a finger groove pattern and a few shards were found painted purple.<ref name=":12" /> A few pots were perforated and the significance of that is not yet known.<ref name=":22" />
== 1964 excavation == In this excavation, a one room Neolithic circular house was excavated.<ref name=":22" /> The wall was made with bamboo and clay and the floor was covered in potholes.<ref name=":22" /> There was a hearth in the center of the house, and there is evidence of it being burned.<ref name=":22" /> Other than the house structure, a few [[terracotta]] figurines in the shape of birds or bulls were also found as well as more [[Stone tool|stone tools]] and pottery.<ref name=":22" /> Animal remains were also collected, the majority of which were cow bones.<ref name=":22" />
==Earliest agriculturists== The people who settled at Sanganakallu were early agriculturists, who cultivated small [[Millet|millets]] and [[Legume|pulses]].<ref name=":0" /> They kept sheep, cattle, and had separate areas for dumping dung ([[Neolithic ashmounds (India)|ash mounds]]).<ref name=":0" />
